<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-840-010  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 840 010.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Learning  Sept 1990 v10 n1 p72(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Political winds propel cruise. (educational technology)</TITLE><AUTHOR>November, Alan.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>At the East/West Invitational Seminar on New Technologies inEducation in the Soviet Union, held on a cruise ship, the talksbegan and ended with an impassioned political statement aboutfreedom or the control of information.andP;  Reflecting on the UnitedStates's own educational technology industry, one wonders if theprofit logic that motivates companies to manufacture products thatsell well, rather than educate well, will dominate.andP;  The triptaken to a different political legacy has motivated this educatorto rethink teaching US students such things as socialresponsibility and political action, encouraging them to becomeactive participants in communities.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Educational AdministrationTechnologyPoliticsEducation.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>